					<p>The United Nations estimates that, by 2015, the world will need to increase food production by 50% if we are to avoid global food shortages. Biotechnology will be a critical tool in meeting this goal. Yet, several hurdles stand in the way of progress, especially for developing countries (Source: Indira Nath, Nature 456 (40), 30 October 2008).</p>
