						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Education-in-developing-world-a-top-priority" title="Education in developing world 'a top priority'" alt="link">Education in developing world 'a top priority'</a></h2>

	
					<p>Catherine Bréchignac, incoming president of the International Council for Science (ICSU), has said that “in the developing world, we need to push e-education [online learning] in order to help young people reach the level of learning required to be good scientists&quot;. ICSU has opened three regional offices for Africa, Asia Pacific, and Latin America and the Caribbean to &quot;ensure that the voice of developing countries influences the international agenda and that scientists from the South are not only involved in research in frontier areas but also have the capacity to address problems of local and regional context&quot;, outgoing ICSU president, Indian chemist Goverdhan Mehta said in his address to the assembly (Source: Carol Campbell, SciDev, 24 October 2008).</p>
							<p><span class="date">4/11/2008</span></p>
